        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Like father like son</h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Peter Lewis took Progressive Insurance from a small operation in Mayfield Village, Ohio, to the <strong>third-largest auto insurer in the US and became a billionaire</strong>. As CEO from 1965 to 2000, his impact went far beyond profits. He revolutionized the auto insurance industry by prioritizing customer service and innovative business strategies.
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/like-father-like-son.png" alt="A picture from the Progressive commercial depicting a truck passing Mount Rushmore" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            Progressive Insurance’s “Mount Rushmore” commercial. Credits: Adforum.com
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Progressive Insurance was <strong>founded in 1937</strong> by Peter’s father, <strong>Joseph Lewis, and Jack Green</strong>. As young lawyers, they saw an opportunity to provide vehicle owners with financial security and protection. Joseph Lewis remained focused on auto coverage. His most defining gamble was <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;"  href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-08-02-2025-1-insuring-high-risk-drivers?source=website" target="_blank">insuring high-risk drivers</a>. By leveraging advanced technology to assess risk accurately, Progressive found profitability in this overlooked market, charging higher premiums.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Peter Lewis lost his father while still in high school. After graduating from Princeton, <strong>he joined Progressive as an underwriting trainee</strong>. He had a knack for finding profitability in unorthodox ideas and a genuine passion for the industry. In 1965, Lewis and his mother used their stock in Progressive as collateral to borrow $2.5 million. They used this money <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-08-02-2025-2-to-buy-out?source=website" target="_blank">to buy out</a> the remaining stockholders. Subsequently, Peter Lewis became CEO. 
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

